  <p>
    The wealth advisor who has practiced long enough eventually encounters the case that no single professional can manage alone. A family patriarch's cognitive decline is accelerating, his estate plan requires revision, his business partners are maneuvering for control, one adult child is threatening litigation, another is in active addiction, and the family's name has appeared in a reporter's inquiry. The advisor recognizes, with a clarity that arrives only through experience, that this situation requires not just expertise but orchestration — the deliberate assembly and sustained coordination of professionals across disciplines that rarely speak to one another, operating under confidentiality frameworks that do not naturally align, each bringing a perspective that is essential and each carrying assumptions that may conflict with those of every other member of the team.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the multidisciplinary advisory team: the constellation of specialists that complex family situations demand. Building one well is among the most consequential skills in advanced advisory practice. Building one poorly — assembling talented professionals without clear roles, communication protocols, or a shared understanding of the engagement's objectives — produces an outcome that is worse than no team at all. Conflicting advice paralyzes the family. Professional egos collide. Confidential information migrates across boundaries that should have been maintained. The family, already in distress, finds itself managing the team rather than being served by it.
  </p>

  <p>
    What follows is a practitioner's framework for assembling, coordinating, and sustaining multidisciplinary teams in the context of complex family situations involving significant wealth. It addresses team composition, role delineation, communication architecture, confidentiality management, conflict resolution, engagement models, specialist vetting, and the long-duration coordination that distinguishes competent team management from the improvisation that passes for it.
  </p>

  <h2>The Anatomy of the Multidisciplinary Team</h2>

  <p>
    The composition of a multidisciplinary team is determined by the situation, not by a template. A cognitive decline scenario requires different professionals than a substance use crisis, and a family governance dispute demands different expertise than a reputational emergency. Nevertheless, certain roles recur with sufficient frequency that the experienced advisor maintains a working understanding of each discipline, a vetted roster of practitioners in each category, and a clear model for how these professionals integrate with one another and with the advisor's own practice.
  </p>

  <h3>The Wealth Advisor</h3>

  <p>
    The wealth advisor — whether a registered investment advisor, a trust officer, a family office director, or another fiduciary — serves as the engagement's originating professional and its primary coordination point. This is not because the advisor possesses the broadest expertise. It is because the advisor holds the deepest relationship with the family, the most comprehensive understanding of the family's financial architecture, and the operational infrastructure to manage a complex, multi-party engagement. The advisor's role on the team is that of convener and coordinator. They are not the decision-maker on clinical, legal, or security matters. They are the professional who ensures that each specialist's contribution is integrated into a coherent strategy that serves the family's interests as a whole.
  </p>

  <h3>Legal Counsel</h3>

  <p>
    Complex family situations require legal involvement, and the relevant legal expertise is rarely concentrated in a single attorney. The family's estate planning counsel may be superb at trust design but unfamiliar with involuntary commitment statutes. The family's corporate attorney may understand the governance implications of a principal's incapacity but have no experience with the family law dimensions of a contested conservatorship. The advisor must understand which legal subspecialties a given situation requires and ensure that appropriate counsel is engaged. Common legal roles on multidisciplinary teams include estate planning attorneys, trust and fiduciary counsel, family law practitioners, criminal defense attorneys, mental health and guardianship specialists, healthcare regulatory counsel, corporate and governance attorneys, and media and defamation specialists. In particularly complex engagements, a lead attorney may serve as legal coordinator, managing the interplay among multiple legal professionals much as the advisor manages the broader team.
  </p>

  <h3>The Certified Public Accountant</h3>

  <p>
    The CPA's role on a multidisciplinary team extends well beyond tax compliance. In situations involving cognitive decline, the CPA may be the first professional to detect anomalies in spending patterns, unusual transactions, or financial exploitation. In substance use cases, the CPA can identify the financial footprint of the disorder — unexplained withdrawals, lifestyle expenditures inconsistent with stated income, charitable pledges made during manic episodes. In family governance disputes, the CPA provides the financial transparency that either substantiates or refutes competing claims. The CPA should be engaged early, briefed on the nature of the situation to the extent that confidentiality permits, and asked to provide the financial intelligence that other team members need to perform their roles effectively.
  </p>

  <h3>Clinical Psychologist or Psychiatrist</h3>

  <p>
    When a family situation involves behavioral health — and the situations that require multidisciplinary teams do — the team requires a clinical professional who can assess the affected individual's condition, recommend appropriate levels of care, evaluate treatment options, and provide ongoing clinical guidance to the team. The distinction between a psychologist and a psychiatrist is relevant: a psychiatrist is a physician who can prescribe medication and is essential when pharmacological management is part of the clinical picture. A psychologist brings depth in psychological assessment, psychotherapy, and behavioral analysis that complements the psychiatrist's medical orientation. In many engagements, both are needed.
  </p>

  <p>
    The clinical professional's role on the multidisciplinary team is advisory to the team and therapeutic to the individual. These roles can create tension. The clinician owes a duty of confidentiality to their patient that may limit what they can share with the team, even when the team believes broader disclosure would improve coordination. The advisor must respect this boundary and build communication protocols that accommodate it rather than pressuring the clinician to compromise their professional obligations.
  </p>

  <h3>Family Therapist or Family Systems Consultant</h3>

  <p>
    The family therapist addresses the relational dynamics that both cause and result from the presenting crisis. Individual treatment addresses the affected family member's condition. Family therapy addresses the system in which that condition exists — the patterns of enabling, the alliances and estrangements, the intergenerational transmission of dysfunction, the communication failures that allowed the situation to reach its current severity. A skilled family therapist who understands the particular dynamics of wealth — entitlement structures, power asymmetries created by differential access to family resources, the weaponization of inheritance, the isolation that accompanies extreme affluence — is an essential team member in any engagement involving family conflict or behavioral health.
  </p>

  <p>
    The family therapist's contribution is distinct from the clinical psychologist's or psychiatrist's. The individual clinician focuses on the patient. The family therapist focuses on the system. Both perspectives are necessary, and the advisor should ensure that the team's structure accommodates both without creating confusion about whose guidance governs which decisions.
  </p>

  <h3>Crisis Communications Specialist</h3>

  <p>
    When a family's situation carries reputational risk — and in an era of ubiquitous digital exposure, the threshold for reputational risk is lower than most families appreciate — a crisis communications professional becomes essential. This specialist manages media inquiries, monitors digital and social media for emerging threats, develops holding statements, prepares family members for potential public exposure, and coordinates with legal counsel on the intersection between communication strategy and legal risk. The crisis communicator should be engaged proactively, before media attention materializes, rather than reactively after the family's situation has become public. Proactive engagement allows the communicator to shape the information environment. Reactive engagement limits them to damage containment.
  </p>

  <h3>Security Consultant</h3>

  <p>
    Security professionals are relevant when the family situation involves physical risk — threats to person or property, stalking, domestic violence, kidnapping risk, or the security implications of a family member's erratic behavior. The security consultant assesses threats, designs protective protocols, coordinates with law enforcement when appropriate, and ensures that the physical safety of family members and staff is maintained throughout the engagement. In substance use and mental health crises, security considerations are more common than many advisors initially recognize. An individual in a manic or psychotic state may pose a risk to themselves or others. A family member in active addiction may be involved with individuals who present a security threat. A contested conservatorship may provoke threatening behavior from the individual subject to the proceeding. The security consultant should be briefed on the clinical and legal dimensions of the situation so that their protective measures account for the full risk landscape.
  </p>

  <h3>Professional Liaison or Therapeutic Consultant</h3>

  <p>
    A therapeutic consultant — sometimes called an educational consultant, a behavioral health case manager, or a professional liaison — serves as the bridge between the family and the clinical treatment system. This professional evaluates the affected individual's clinical needs, identifies appropriate treatment facilities or clinical providers, facilitates admissions, monitors treatment progress, advocates for the individual within the treatment system, and coordinates transitions between levels of care. The therapeutic consultant's value is greatest when the family is navigating the treatment landscape for the first time, when the situation involves co-occurring disorders that require specialized expertise, or when previous treatment episodes have failed and a more carefully matched clinical approach is needed.
  </p>

  <p>
    The therapeutic consultant is not a clinician providing direct treatment. They are a navigator — a professional whose knowledge of the treatment ecosystem allows the family to make informed decisions about clinical placement and whose ongoing monitoring ensures that the treatment is producing the outcomes the clinical plan contemplated.
  </p>

  <h2>Role Clarification and Scope Boundaries</h2>

  <p>
    The most common failure in multidisciplinary team management is ambiguity about who is responsible for what. When roles are undefined, critical tasks fall between professionals, duplicative efforts create confusion, and the family receives conflicting guidance from team members who each believe they are providing advice within their proper scope. The advisor who convenes the team bears responsibility for establishing explicit role delineation at the engagement's outset and maintaining it throughout.
  </p>

  <p>
    Role clarification begins with a written engagement framework — not a formal contract between team members, but a document that articulates each professional's scope of responsibility, the decisions that fall within their authority, the decisions that require consultation with other team members, and the decisions that are reserved to the family. This framework should address the following questions for each team member:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Scope of engagement:</strong> What specific issues is this professional responsible for addressing? What falls outside their scope?</li>
    <li><strong>Decision authority:</strong> What decisions can this professional make independently, and which require consultation with other team members or approval from the family?</li>
    <li><strong>Information access:</strong> What information does this professional need to perform their role, and what information should they not receive?</li>
    <li><strong>Communication obligations:</strong> When and how should this professional communicate with the coordinator and with other team members?</li>
    <li><strong>Deliverables:</strong> What tangible work product is expected, and on what timeline?</li>
    <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Is this professional engaged for a defined period, until a specific milestone, or on an ongoing basis?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Scope boundaries require particular attention at the intersections between disciplines. The attorney and the therapist may both have views on whether a family meeting should take place. The psychiatrist and the family office director may disagree about whether an individual's capacity is sufficient to execute a financial transaction. The crisis communicator and the attorney may have incompatible instincts about how to respond to a media inquiry. The engagement framework should anticipate these intersections and establish protocols for resolving them, rather than leaving the family to adjudicate professional disagreements in real time.
  </p>

  <h2>Communication Architecture</h2>

  <p>
    Effective multidisciplinary coordination depends on communication protocols that are designed with intention rather than allowed to develop by default. The advisor should establish the following communication structures at the engagement's outset.
  </p>

  <h3>The Coordination Call</h3>

  <p>
    A regularly scheduled conference among all team members — or all team members whose roles overlap sufficiently to warrant joint communication — serves as the engagement's primary coordination mechanism. The frequency depends on the situation's urgency: daily during an acute crisis, weekly during active management, monthly during extended engagements. The coordination call should follow a structured agenda: status updates from each professional, identification of emerging issues, decisions required, and assignments for the interval until the next call. The advisor or their designee chairs the call, maintains minutes, and distributes action items.
  </p>

  <h3>Bilateral Communication</h3>

  <p>
    Not all communication should flow through the full team. The attorney and the CPA may need to discuss tax implications of a trust modification without involving the therapist. The psychiatrist and the therapeutic consultant may need to discuss clinical progress without involving the attorney. Bilateral communication should be encouraged when it serves efficiency, but the coordinator should be copied or briefed on any bilateral exchange that affects the overall engagement strategy. The principle is transparency to the coordination function without requiring every professional to absorb every communication.
  </p>

  <h3>Family Communication</h3>

  <p>
    The team must present a unified front to the family. Conflicting advice delivered by different professionals erodes the family's confidence and creates opportunities for family members to selectively adopt the guidance that confirms their existing preferences. The engagement framework should designate which professionals communicate directly with the family and under what circumstances. In many engagements, the advisor serves as the primary family contact, synthesizing input from the team and presenting recommendations in a form the family can act upon. Individual professionals may communicate directly with the family on matters within their specific scope, but strategic recommendations should be coordinated before delivery.
  </p>

  <h3>Documentation and Records</h3>

  <p>
    Every significant communication, decision, and action should be documented contemporaneously. This documentation serves multiple functions: it provides a coordination reference for the team, it establishes a record of fiduciary diligence, it supports continuity when team members transition, and it creates the institutional memory that informs future engagements. The advisor should establish a documentation protocol that specifies what is recorded, where records are maintained, who has access, and how long they are retained. Given the sensitivity of the information involved, the documentation system must be secure, access-controlled, and compliant with applicable privacy regulations.
  </p>

  <h2>Confidentiality Frameworks Across Disciplines</h2>

  <p>
    Each professional on a multidisciplinary team operates under a confidentiality framework that is specific to their discipline, and these frameworks do not align naturally. The attorney's communications with the client are protected by attorney-client privilege, which can be waived only by the client and which may be destroyed if the communication is shared with third parties. The physician's and psychologist's communications with the patient are protected by HIPAA and, for substance use treatment information, by 42 CFR Part 2. The CPA's communications are protected by a more limited confidentiality obligation that varies by jurisdiction. The crisis communicator and security consultant operate under contractual confidentiality provisions rather than statutory protections.
  </p>

  <p>
    The practical consequence of these overlapping frameworks is that information cannot flow freely among team members without careful attention to privilege and consent. Sharing attorney-client privileged information with a therapist may waive the privilege. Sharing clinical information with the advisory team without the patient's written authorization may violate HIPAA. The advisor must work with the team's legal counsel to design an information-sharing architecture that enables effective coordination while preserving each discipline's confidentiality protections. Common mechanisms include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Common interest agreements:</strong> Legal arrangements that allow multiple parties' attorneys to share privileged information without waiving privilege, where the parties share a common legal interest.</li>
    <li><strong>HIPAA authorizations:</strong> Written consents from the individual that permit specific clinical information to be shared with designated team members for defined purposes.</li>
    <li><strong>Information compartmentalization:</strong> Structuring team communications so that each professional receives only the information necessary for their specific role, rather than full access to all information across all disciplines.</li>
    <li><strong>Joint defense or common interest privilege:</strong> In situations involving potential litigation, arrangements that protect communications among team members who share a common defensive interest.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The confidentiality architecture should be established at the engagement's outset, documented in writing, and reviewed whenever the team's composition or the engagement's scope changes. It is far easier to design these protections prospectively than to reconstruct them after information has already been shared in ways that compromise privilege or violate consent requirements.
  </p>

  <h2>Managing Conflicting Professional Opinions</h2>

  <p>
    Professional disagreement is not a sign of team dysfunction. It is an inherent feature of multidisciplinary work. A psychiatrist and a family therapist may disagree about whether an individual is ready to resume family contact. An attorney and a crisis communicator may hold opposing views on whether to issue a public statement. A security consultant and a clinical psychologist may assess the same individual's risk profile differently. These disagreements reflect genuine differences in professional training, risk tolerance, and disciplinary orientation. They are valuable precisely because they surface considerations that a single-discipline approach would miss.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor's role is not to resolve professional disagreements by choosing sides. It is to ensure that disagreements are surfaced constructively, that each professional's perspective is heard, that the implications of each position are clearly articulated to the family, and that the family is positioned to make an informed decision. The engagement framework should establish a protocol for managing disagreements that includes the following elements:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct professional dialogue:</strong> Before a disagreement is escalated to the family, the professionals involved should discuss their positions directly, with the coordinator present. The disagreement is narrower than it initially appears, and a synthesis is achievable.</li>
    <li><strong>Written position statements:</strong> When a disagreement cannot be resolved through dialogue, each professional should articulate their position in writing, including the reasoning, the risks of the alternative approach, and the conditions under which they would revise their recommendation.</li>
    <li><strong>Domain deference:</strong> On matters that fall clearly within a single discipline, the team should defer to the specialist in that discipline. The psychiatrist's assessment of clinical risk should carry more weight than the attorney's opinion on the same question, just as the attorney's analysis of legal exposure should carry more weight than the psychiatrist's.</li>
    <li><strong>Family decision authority:</strong> Ultimately, the family — not the team — makes the decisions that affect the family's interests. The team's role is to ensure that these decisions are informed by the best available professional judgment across all relevant disciplines. The family may accept one professional's recommendation and decline another's. This is their prerogative, and the team should respect it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Advisor as Coordinator Versus Participant</h2>

  <p>
    The advisor who convenes a multidisciplinary team must maintain disciplined clarity about their dual role. They are simultaneously a participant in the engagement — contributing their own professional expertise on financial, fiduciary, and operational matters — and the coordinator of the broader team effort. These roles can conflict.
  </p>

  <p>
    As a participant, the advisor has substantive views on the family's situation and may advocate for specific approaches. As a coordinator, the advisor must create space for other professionals to offer perspectives that may differ from the advisor's own. The coordinator who allows their participant role to dominate the engagement — filtering information through their own perspective, steering team recommendations toward their preferred outcome, or marginalizing professionals whose input complicates the advisor's preferred strategy — undermines the multidisciplinary model and deprives the family of the diverse expertise the team was assembled to provide.
  </p>

  <p>
    The discipline required is straightforward in principle and difficult in practice: the advisor must advocate their professional views on financial and fiduciary matters with clarity and conviction, while simultaneously ensuring that the team's overall recommendations reflect the genuine integration of every relevant perspective. When the advisor's participant views conflict with other professionals' recommendations, the advisor should disclose this tension to the family rather than suppressing it.
  </p>

  <p>
    In engagements of sufficient complexity, separating the coordinator and participant roles entirely — engaging a professional project manager or engagement coordinator who does not have substantive advisory responsibilities — can resolve this tension. This is particularly valuable in high-conflict situations where the family's existing advisor may be perceived by some family members as aligned with a particular faction.
  </p>

  <h2>Fee Structures and Engagement Models</h2>

  <p>
    Multidisciplinary teams create fee complexity that the family should understand before the engagement begins. Each professional bills according to their own fee structure: attorneys charge hourly, therapists may charge per session or by retainer, crisis communicators work on monthly retainers, security consultants may charge hourly or by project, and therapeutic consultants may charge a combination of fixed fees and hourly rates. The aggregate cost of a complex engagement can be substantial, and the family deserves transparency about the anticipated financial commitment.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor should present the family with a fee framework at the engagement's outset that addresses the following:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Individual fee structures:</strong> Each professional's billing methodology, rate, and anticipated time commitment.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggregate cost estimates:</strong> A realistic projection of total costs over the anticipated engagement period, including a range that accounts for the engagement's inherent unpredictability.</li>
    <li><strong>Billing coordination:</strong> Whether each professional bills the family independently or whether the advisor consolidates billing. Independent billing is simpler administratively but requires the family to manage multiple invoices. Consolidated billing provides a single point of financial accountability but creates additional work for the advisor and may raise questions about fee arrangements among professionals.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope management:</strong> Mechanisms for controlling costs as the engagement evolves, including periodic budget reviews, authorization thresholds for significant expenditures, and clear protocols for expanding or reducing the team's scope.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The advisor should be transparent about their own compensation in the context of the team engagement. If the advisor receives referral fees, revenue-sharing arrangements, or other compensation from team members, these arrangements must be disclosed. The fiduciary standard demands that the advisor's recommendations about team composition be driven by the family's needs and not by the advisor's financial interests.
  </p>

  <h2>Vetting Specialists</h2>

  <p>
    The quality of a multidisciplinary team depends entirely on the quality of its individual members, and the process of identifying and evaluating specialists for complex family engagements is more demanding than many advisors appreciate. Credentials and reputation are necessary but insufficient criteria. The relevant question is not merely whether a professional is competent in their discipline but whether they can function effectively within a multidisciplinary framework — communicating across professional boundaries, respecting the contributions of professionals from other disciplines, maintaining confidentiality under complex constraints, and subordinating their individual professional identity to the team's collective mission.
  </p>

  <p>
    Effective vetting should assess the following dimensions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Technical competence:</strong> Verified credentials, relevant subspecialty experience, and a track record with cases of comparable complexity. References should be sought from professionals in other disciplines who have worked with the individual on multidisciplinary engagements, not merely from colleagues within their own field.</li>
    <li><strong>UHNW experience:</strong> Familiarity with the particular dynamics of significant wealth — the enabling infrastructure, the privacy requirements, the governance structures, the family dynamics that wealth creates and intensifies. A clinician who is excellent with general populations may be unprepared for the specific challenges that UHNW clients present.</li>
    <li><strong>Team orientation:</strong> Willingness to operate within a structured team framework, to defer on matters outside their expertise, and to communicate through established protocols rather than independently pursuing their own agenda with the family.</li>
    <li><strong>Confidentiality discipline:</strong> A demonstrated commitment to confidentiality that extends beyond legal compliance to include the discretion and judgment that complex family situations demand. The professional who is technically compliant with HIPAA but casually discusses client situations in professional settings is a liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Availability and responsiveness:</strong> Complex family situations do not respect business hours or calendar availability. The specialist who cannot be reached during a crisis, who is unavailable for coordination calls, or whose other commitments consistently delay their contribution undermines the team's effectiveness regardless of their individual excellence.</li>
    <li><strong>Conflict of interest screening:</strong> Verification that the specialist has no existing relationships with other parties to the family situation — other family members, business counterparts, opposing counsel, or competing interests — that would compromise their objectivity or create confidentiality conflicts.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The advisor should maintain a curated roster of vetted specialists across relevant disciplines, updated regularly based on engagement experience and peer feedback. This roster is among the most valuable assets in the advisor's practice. Building it requires years of deliberate relationship development, and no amount of last-minute searching during a crisis can substitute for the preparatory work of identifying, evaluating, and cultivating relationships with outstanding professionals across the relevant disciplines.
  </p>

  <h2>Maintaining Team Cohesion During Extended Engagements</h2>

  <p>
    Many multidisciplinary engagements extend over months or years. A contested conservatorship may involve years of litigation. A family member's recovery from substance use disorder may require ongoing clinical coordination for an extended period. A family governance restructuring may take years from initiation to full implementation. Over these extended timeframes, the team faces challenges that short-duration engagements do not: professional fatigue, changing family dynamics, turnover among team members, scope creep, budget erosion, and the gradual attenuation of the urgency that originally motivated the family to invest in a coordinated team response.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor can sustain team cohesion through several deliberate practices:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Periodic strategic reviews:</strong> At defined intervals — quarterly in most engagements — the team should step back from operational management and assess the engagement's trajectory. Are the original objectives still relevant? Has the situation evolved in ways that require changes to the team's composition or strategy? Are any team members no longer necessary, and are there emerging needs that require additional expertise?</li>
    <li><strong>Explicit acknowledgment of contributions:</strong> Professionals who feel that their expertise is valued and their contributions are recognized remain engaged and committed. The advisor should ensure that each team member's contribution is visible to the family and to the rest of the team.</li>
    <li><strong>Managed transitions:</strong> When a team member must be replaced — due to departure, performance concerns, changed circumstances, or the natural conclusion of their specific scope — the transition should be managed deliberately. Knowledge transfer, introduction of the replacement to the team, and updating the engagement framework are all necessary steps that are neglected when transitions occur mid-engagement.</li>
    <li><strong>Scope and budget recalibration:</strong> Long engagements inevitably exceed their original scope and budget projections. Rather than allowing costs to accumulate without acknowledgment, the advisor should proactively recalibrate the engagement's scope and budget at each strategic review, presenting the family with updated projections and securing continued authorization for the team's work.</li>
    <li><strong>Relationship maintenance between active phases:</strong> In engagements that involve alternating periods of activity and dormancy — as when a family member is in treatment and the team's involvement is reduced to monitoring — the advisor should maintain periodic contact with team members to preserve relationships, provide status updates, and ensure that the team can be remobilized efficiently when the situation requires it.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The Long View</h2>

  <p>
    The multidisciplinary advisory team is not a permanent structure. It is a purposeful assembly of professionals, convened to address a specific situation, sustained as long as the situation requires coordinated expertise, and dissolved when its work is complete. But the capability to assemble and manage such a team — the relationships with vetted specialists, the frameworks for coordination and communication, the experience with confidentiality management and conflict resolution — is a permanent and compounding asset in the advisor's practice.
  </p>

  <p>
    The advisor who develops this capability offers something that no individual specialist can provide: the ability to perceive a complex family situation whole, to identify the disciplines it requires, to assemble the right professionals, and to orchestrate their collective effort toward an outcome that serves the family's interests across every dimension — financial, legal, clinical, relational, reputational, and operational. This is not project management. It is the highest expression of the advisory function: the recognition that the most consequential work in wealth advisory is not the management of assets but the coordination of expertise in service of families whose situations demand nothing less.
  </p>

  <p>
    The families who need this capability most are those who have experienced what happens in its absence — the crisis that was managed by a single professional operating beyond their competence, the family dispute that escalated because legal and therapeutic perspectives were never integrated, the treatment episode that failed because clinical and financial coordination were neglected. For these families, the advisor who can build and manage a genuine multidisciplinary team does not merely add value. They provide the architecture within which every other professional's contribution becomes effective.
  </p>

